        "stress-info-title": "What is chronic water stress?",
        "stress-info-1": "Chronic water stress is a condition in which water demand exceeds the available supply for a long period of time. <b>This means that in Cyprus we consume more water than what can be naturally replenished by rainfall</b>, and as a result, we need technical means to cover the remaining needs.",
        "stress-info-2": "Cyprus faces a high level of water stress, placing it among the five most vulnerable countries in the world. <b>Indicatively, the available natural water resources are only 390 cubic meters (mÂ³) per year per person (â‰ˆ 1070 liters per day, covering all societal needs), while the extreme water scarcity threshold is set at 500 mÂ³/year, and the general water scarcity threshold at 1,000 mÂ³/year (â‰ˆ 2740 liters per day)</b>. At the European level, water scarcity and droughts cost up to â‚¬9 billion annually, affect 30% of citizens and 20% of land each year, while almost half of Europeans consider them the greatest threat to their country's water reserves.",
        "stress-info-3": "The main factors that burden water stress are population growth, tourism development, agricultural activity and climate change, which causes significant reduction in rainfall. <b>Indicatively, water demand in Cyprus during the period 2019-2023 increased by 15%, while at the same time dam capacity in June 2025 was below 20%, while during the corresponding period in 2024 it was double (40%)</b>.",
        "stress-info-4a": "To address chronic water stress and the reduction of available water resources due to prolonged drought during 2023-2025, <b>the Ministry of Agriculture, Rural Development and Environment has taken a series of measures, such as the installation of additional desalination units, as well as the subsidization of upgrades to water supply networks, many of which are expected to be completed during 2026-2027.</b>",
        "stress-info-4b": "These measures, combined with ongoing projects by EOA and the Water Development Department (WDD), such as the use of smart water meters and the installation of additional sensors and advanced monitoring and control software, <b>will significantly enhance our long-term water security, especially for drinking water, allowing more flexibility in managing the remaining quantities for irrigation</b>.",
        "stress-info-5a": "However, as current needs exceed available water quantities, <b>it is important to limit unnecessary water consumption, thus helping organizations manage water shortages without supply cuts, which cause medium-term additional damages and leaks</b>. Today, it is estimated that average household consumption remains at 140 liters per person per day, while the EU average has fallen to 124 liters per person (approximately 10% less than the average consumption in Cyprus).",
        "stress-info-5b": "At the same time, <b>the new European water resilience strategy calls on countries to set as a pan-European goal the reduction of water use by at least 10% by 2030, as well as to determine their own targets based on their conditions</b>. Specifically, various funding programs will be announced, targeting water consumption reduction, adoption of digital technologies and improvement of water quality.",
        "action-info-title": "How do small changes make a big difference?",
        "action-info-1": "Beyond desalination, the application of new technologies and upgrading networks to reduce losses, <b>we need to make conservative use of water</b>. Although household drinking water supply accounts for about ~20% of Cyprus' total consumption (~50 million mÂ³ out of 266), every liter we save helps maintain the quality of our aquifers and reduce dependence on desalination, which is energy-intensive and environmentally burdensome, while helping to ensure additional quantities of good quality water for agriculture.",
        "action-info-2": "Reducing water use by 1 minute per person per day may seem small, but multiplied by Cyprus' population (~1 million) it creates a huge impact (1 minute Ã— 10 liters/minute Ã— 1 million people Ã— 365 days = 3.65 million mÂ³ of water annually, equivalent to the total volume of Nicosia dams, or Polemidia dam!)",
        "action-info-3": "This amount of water can supply 70,000 people for a year, or cover almost the needs of Paphos District.",
        "action-info-4": "Additionally, water conservation provides greater <b>flexibility in utilizing the quantities remaining in dams</b>, combined with desalination, reducing costs for the consumer, as well as greenhouse gas emissions.",
